subsection.p:
A small change dt sweeps out a small arc length. Since \mathbf r'(t)=(-3\sin t,3\cos t), we have \|\mathbf r'(t)\| = \sqrt{9\sin^2t+9\cos^2t} = 3. So ds=3\,dt. A small piece of wire has mass approximately \rho(\mathbf r(t))\,ds = (2+\cos t)3\,dt. Adding all pieces gives
M \amp= \int_0^\pi (2+\cos t)3\,dt \amp= 3\left[2t+\sin t\right]_0^\pi \amp= 6\pi.
So the wire has mass \boxed{ 6\pi \text{ grams}. }

