    \node at (0,-0.9) {\(\rho(x,y)=2+\frac{x}{3}\)};
\end{tikzpicture}

statement.p:
Along the wire, \rho(\mathbf r(t))=1+\frac t2. Also, \mathbf r'(t)=\left(1,1,\frac12\right), so \|\mathbf r'(t)\| = \sqrt{1+1+\frac14} = \frac32. Therefore
M \amp= \int_C \rho\,ds \amp= \int_0^2 \left(1+\frac t2\right)\frac32\,dt \amp= \frac32\left[t+\frac{t^2}{4}\right]_0^2 \amp= \frac32(2+1) \amp= \frac92.
So the wire has mass \boxed{ \frac92 \text{ kilograms}. }

subsection.md:
\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{Step} \amp \text{Action} \\ \hline
1 \amp \text{Parametrize the curve: }\mathbf r(t).\\[1mm]
2 \amp \text{Evaluate the scalar field on the curve: }f(\mathbf r(t)).\\[1mm]
3 \amp \text{Multiply by speed: }\|\mathbf r'(t)\|\,dt.
\end{array}

statement.p:
Define
\mathbf r(t)= \begin{cases} (t,\;t\sin(1/t)), \amp 0\lt t\le1,\\ (0,0), \amp t=0. \end{cases}
This curve is continuous, but it wiggles infinitely often near the origin. Its length is infinite. Therefore \int_C 1\,ds does not give a finite number.

On the line segment \mathbf r(t)=(t,0), \qquad 0\le t\le1, define
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} 1, \amp x \text{ rational},\\ 0, \amp x \text{ irrational}. \end{cases}
Every subinterval contains rational and irrational x-values. Riemann sums can be forced toward 1 or toward 0, depending on sample points. There is no single settled value.

A cable runs from (0,0) to (4,3). The temperature on the floor is T(x,y)=18+x-\frac{y}{3}. Parametrize the cable by \mathbf r(t)=(4t,3t), \qquad 0\le t\le1. Then T(\mathbf r(t)) = 18+4t-\frac{3t}{3} = 18+3t. Also, \|\mathbf r'(t)\|=\|(4,3)\|=5. The length is L=\int_0^1 5\,dt=5. The average temperature is
T_{\mathrm{avg}} \amp= \frac{1}{5}\int_0^1 (18+3t)5\,dt \amp= \int_0^1(18+3t)\,dt \amp= 18+\frac32 \amp= \frac{39}{2}.
So the average temperature along the cable is \boxed{ 19.5^\circ\text{C}. }
